Text Mining to Decipher Free-Response Consumer Complaints
¶

OBJECTIVE¶

The objective of this study is to identify clusters of vehicle related problem and associated year trends after 2012. Incidents representing two severity levels(fatal incidents and incidents involving injury) from the free response data in the NHTSA's vehicls owner's complaint database are analyzed using text mining approach.

METHOD¶

Vehicle Owner's Complaint Database

The vehicle owner's complaint database in this study contains 4,39,414 incidents reported since 2012. The analysis focused exclusively on the description part provided by drivers of the database. Two additional columns INJURED and DEATHS are used to identify clusters. In those two columns, two severity levels i.e. (a) incidents involving at least one injury and no deaths and (b) incidents involving at least one death are analyzed. Incidents involving atleast 1 death accounted for approximately 0.12% of the database and incidents involving injury accounted for approximately 0.3% of the database. Since, there is a disparity between number of complaints in each severity level, a uniform random sample of 400 complaints involving injury are analyzed. The two severity levels are shown in the first two rows of the Table 1.

Data Preprocessing

The description column of the database is preprocessed before creating clusters. The preprocessing is common in text mining and includes removing punctuation, stemming the words and removing the stopwords. Further, words greater than 2 characters were used in the analysis as there are some certain unnecesserary 2 character words which could have skewed the clusters.

After preprocessing the description part, a term-document matrix is created. In the term-document matrix, each row corresponds to a term in the corpus and each column to a complaint. The values in each cell represents frequency of a term in each row and in each complaint.

Dimensionality reduction

Term-Document matrix contains terms of low frequency which may not be of interest to us. Thus, it is necessary to reduce dimensionality of our term-document matrix. LSA provides an efficient way of identifying similar documents by reducing the dimensionality of the term-document matrix. Dimensionality reduction is achieved through Singular value decomposition performed on the term-document matrix.

RESULTS¶

The clusters were made using Hierarchical Clustering Method. Clustering was stopped one step before a split occured that resulted in two different clusters with the same most frequent terms.

Cluster analysis identified eight clusters of fatal accidents and five clusters of incidents involving injury.

Fatal Incidents

In the fatal incidents, the clusters which appears to be of interest are 'airbag', 'crash', and 'recal'. The Airbag and recal clusters seems to represent TAKATA airbag issue which affected 42 million cars in the US. The number of deaths associated with TAKATA airbag issue are 18 in the database which is supported by the fact that there has been 22 deaths till date due to faulty TAKATA airbags. From the table above, Honda vehicles are related to most deaths. According to NHTSA, approximately 16.3 millions Honda vehicles are affected by TAKATA airbag issue. Chrysler group(Dodge, Ram and Jeep) vehicles are affected most after Honda vehicles standing at 7.3 million. The term airbag appears in 4 of the clusters.

From the time-trend graph, it can be noticed that recal has a increasing trend after 2014 which may be due to the fact that Vehicle Manufacturers started complying with NHTSA decision to recall all the defective models with faulty TAKATA airbags.

Analysis of the Crash cluster reveals that it is related to Tesla car crashes, especially Model S in the recent years. Out of the 13 complaints, TESLA alone was responsible for 13 deaths with no other manufacturer causing more than 2 deaths. Most of the complaints are related to suspension failures leading to wheel detachment and causing crash. There might be more deaths or injuries caused by faulty TESLA models which may not been been reported to NHTSA as TESLA made their customers sign Non-disclosure agreement. There are four instances of crashes due to Autopilot mode. Tesla's Autopilot mode has stirred a lot of controversy in the past year with the question being "Is Autopilot mode reliable?". However, in an investigation conducted by NTSB, there were no defects found in TESLA's autopilot mode of the car's involved in accidents. NTSB also concluded that Tesla car crash rate dropped by 40% after Autopilot mode was installed.

The time-trend graph of crash cluster shows that number of crashes are increasing over the past few years which may be the result of over-reliance on advanced technologies.

The brake cluster seems to represents sudden unintended acceleration problem which which might still be present in the cars. In 2009, unintended sudden acceleration problem was present prominently in Toyota vehicles followed by Ford vehicles. This issue seems to be the main cause of deaths in Toyota vehicles around 2014.

The brake cluster also represents incidents involving deaths caused by cars equipped with keyless ignition. This issue occured prominently in General Motor vehicles(Chevrolet, Buick, Pontiac) in which faulty ignition switch could shut off engine during a crash and thereby preventing airbags from inflating. In addition to GM vehicles, Lincoln(Ford luxury brand) vehicles were also affected causing 11 deaths. 10 out of 11 deaths due to keyless ignition issue in Lincoln vehicles occured in 2015.

The time-trend graph of brake cluster is concerning because number of accidents are increasing since 2016.

The seat cluster is related to issues with seatbelts, especially child safety seats.

The truck, passeng and contact cluster does not seem to be associated with any particular incident in the past 5 years. The deaths might be the result of any routine problems with the vehicles. However, one particular point of interest is that General Motor and Ford vehicles are associated with most deaths in these three clusters. Faulty airbags not inflating during a crash or contact with another vehicle might be the reason for deaths, but there has been no investigation about it.

The time-trend graphs for truck and contact cluster shows that most of the incidents occured around 2014-15 and they have been decreasing since.

Incidents involving Injury

In the incidents involving injury, five clusters were made using Hierarchical clustering. Two clusters with the same most frequent term 'contact' were made if the dendrogram was cut at 6 clusters. So, clustering was stopped at 5 clusters.

Airbag cluster seems to represent TAKATA airbag issue, even though frequency of the term takata is low, it is same to assume that not every driver is going to mention the term 'takata' in their complaints.

The time-trend graph of airbag cluster reveals that number of injuries related to airbags have been decreasing over the past few years. This could be due to the fact that majority of the manufacturers have recalled the vehicles with faulty airbags.

The Steer cluster is associated with power steering issues with Ford vehicles. In these vehicles,some of the steering gear heat shield fasteners may have a surface finish with insufficient corrosion protection. According to Ford "the heat shield may corrode and detach from the steering gear — exposing the steering gear system to higher than expected temperatures". Ford recalled 4,23,000 vehicles in the year 2015 for the power steering issue. There are 23 injuries related to Ford vehicles associated with Steer cluster.

The time-trend graph of Steer cluster is concerning as it has a increasing trend.
